<br>
Person A: Do you have a car?<br>
<br>
Person B does have a car.<br>
English: Yes, I have a car. (you answer 'yes' because you positively have a car)<br>
Japanese: Yes, I have a car. (you answer 'yes' because you agree with the question)<br>
<br>
Person A: Do you have a car?<br>
<br>
Person B does not have a car.<br>
English: No, I do not have a car. (you answer 'no' because you negatively don't have a car)<br>
Japanese: No, I do not have a car. (you answer 'no' because you disagree with the question)<br>
<br>
Person A: Do you not have a car?<br>
<br>
Person B does have a car.<br>
English: Yes, I have a car. (you answer 'yes' because you positively have a car)<br>
Japanese: No, I have a car. (you answer 'no' because you disagree with the question)<br>
<br>
Person A: Do you not have a car?<br>
<br>
Person B does not have a car.<br>
English: No, I do not have a car. (you answer 'no' because you negatively do not have a car)<br>
Japanese: Yes, I do not have a car. (you answer 'yes' because you agree with the question)<br>
<br>
 To illustrate this in Japanese:<br>
<br>
Kuruma ga arimasuka? (Do you have a car?)<br>
<br>
Hai, kuruma ga arimasu. (Yes, I have a car.)<br>
Or<br>
Iie, kuruma ga arimasen. (No, I do not have a car.)<br>
<br>
Kuruma ga arimasenka? (Do you not have a car?)<br>
<br>
Iie, kuruma ga arimasu. (No, I have a car.)<br>
Or<br>
Hai, kuruma ga arimasen. (Yes, I do not have a car.)<br>
<br>
Clear?<br>
